On 12 June 2024 the Federal Open Market Committee left the federal-funds target range at 5.25%-5.50% for the seventh consecutive meeting.  
The statement cited:  
- twelve-month PCE inflation having “eased” but still “elevated”;  
- slower April-May CPI prints (3.4% headline, 3.6% core);  
- May payrolls rising 272k with unemployment at 4.0%;  
- continued “strong” job gains and “robust” GDP growth (Q1 revised to 1.3% annual rate);  
- unchanged 2% longer-run inflation goal.  
The Committee said it “does not expect it will be appropriate to reduce the target range until it has gained greater confidence that inflation is moving sustainably toward 2%,” signaling one projected cut later this year.
